text.tspan: Nonsuicidal self-injury, often simply called self-injury, is the act of deliberately harming
your own body, such as cutting or burning yourself. It's typically not meant as a suicide
attempt. Rather, this type of self-injury is a harmful way to cope with emotional pain,
Signs and symptoms of self-injury may include:
Fresh cuts, scratches, bruises, bite marks or other wounds
Excessive rubbing of an area to create a burn
Wearing long sleeves or long pants, even in hot weather
Behavioral and emotional instability, impulsivity and
Statements of helplessness, hopelessness or worthlessness

controlled or ritualistic manner that often leaves a
Cutting (cuts or severe scratches with a sharp object)
Burning (with lit matches, cigarettes or heated,
Carving words or symbols on the skin
Piercing the skin with sharp objects
There's no one single or simple cause that leads someone
to self-injure. In general, self-injury may result from:
Poor coping skills. Nonsuicidal self-injury is usually the
result of an inability to cope in healthy ways with
Difficulty managing emotions. The person has a hard time
regulating, expressing or understanding emotions. The mix
of emotions that triggers self-injury is complex. For
instance, there may be feelings of worthlessness,
loneliness, panic, anger, guilt, rejection, self-hatred or
